{[showcards W:DA N:D2]

You are West. The bidding has been as shown. East led the \DA, dummy played the \D2 

Play the \DQ.

As soon as dummy appears you can see 3 tricks for your side. Partner surely has the \DK to go with his Ace and you have a certain trump trick. However, that's all you can see.

Your best hope is that East may be able to win a \S trick, and it may be important for the first \S lead to come from your side of the table.

Your \DQ play informs partner that you also have the \DJ, giving him the option of underleading his \DK to get to your hand.

East next plays a small \D which you win with your \DJ. You return the \ST. This establishes East's \SK before North can pull trumps and discard one of dummy's \Ss on his fourth \C.}
